ce:section.ce:para:
We aimed to relieve HA inhibition on microorganisms in-situ using s-CQDs and p-CQDs. The cumulative CH4 yield was increased by 1.9 times to 350.0 ± 5.0 mL/g VS (Fig. 2(c)) with 3.0 g/L of s-CQDs. Similarly, with high dosage of p-CQDs (3.0 g/L), the cumulative CH4 yield increased by 1.3 times which was 303 ± 14.2 mL/g VS. Nevertheless, the increased p-CQDs addition did not further promote the process. Therefore, a 3.0 g/L s-CQDs dosage was suitable for relieving HA inhibition in-situ. Moreover, addition of s-CQDs led to a shorter lag time and higher theoretical CH4 yield (B

                           0
                        ) compared with p-CQDs (Table S3). A similar phenomenon also occurred in acetic acid AD system with 1.0 g/L HA. Fig. 2(d) showed that addition of 1.0 g/L s-CQDs increased the cumulative CH4 yield to 241.2 ± 15.0 mL/g VS, which was 1.6 times higher than without s-CQDs. After adding 1.0 g/L p-CQDs, the cumulative CH4 yield was 184.8 ± 0.0 mL/g VS, which was 1.0 times higher than that before adding. However, after increasing the dosages by three times, the cumulative CH4 yield did not increase significantly. In the 3.0 g/L s-CQDs system, the cumulative CH4 yield was 245.0 ± 17.5 mL/g VS, and in the 3.0 g/L p-CQDs system, it was 204.4 ± 0.00 mL/g VS. Fig. 2(e) showed that the maximum daily CH4 yield of all ethanol AD system occurred between day 15–20. Both s-CQDs and p-CQDs promoted the daily CH4 yield in 1.0 g/L HA inhibition system, while the increment on daily CH4 yield followed the s-CQDs and p-CQDs dosages, especially s-CQDs. In the acetic acid AD system (Fig. 2(f)), addition of s-CQDs achieved the maximum daily CH4 yield compared to p-CQDs. Although an increased dosage did not improve the maximum daily CH4 yield, it still shortened the time required to reach the maximum value. These results indicated that s-CQDs and p-CQDs effectively relieved HA inhibition in-situ, with s-CQDs being the optimal choice.
